I’ve made several CAN PCBs using 2mm wide traces over the past few years that have worked pretty well.
NGL though, I chose this size entirely arbitrarily (just doubled what the default was in the editor I was using), and they’re pretty short traces so your mileage may vary.

Use the Layer Stack Manager to calculate the correct trace width to target a 120ohm differential impedance. I recommend using a 4 layer board to make this easier. JLC barely charges more for a 4 layer PCB and has stackup details on their site.

Altium – 9 Nov 20

Impedance Calculations and PCB Stackup Design in Altium Designer

Impedance control is a popular design technique in high speed and high frequency PCBs. See how Altium Designer helps you design for impedance control.

If you’re using CAN FD, these small details matter. Altium makes it very easy to get the right impedance - why not make sure of it?

Also, DO NOT add capacitors from CAN lines to GND as your link states! This will ruin the 10 Mbps CAN FD that CTRE runs. More capacitance on CAN lines is bad.
